Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Bring a #large saucepan{} of water with @salt{0.5%tsp} to the boil for the potatoes.

Trim the @carrots{3}, then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Chop into roughly 1cm wide, 5cm long batons.

Halve any large @cauliflower florets{300%g}. Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%can} in a #sieve{}.

Pop the carrots onto half of a #large baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{} and @salt{pinch}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

When your pan of water is boiling, stir in the @ground turmeric{1}, then add the potatoes and cook until you can easily slip a knife through, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once the carrots have roasted for about 5 mins, add the cauliflower to the other half of the same #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{} and @salt{pinch}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Return to the top shelf to roast for the remaining time until golden brown and tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Turn both veg halfway through.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the garlic and @korma curry paste{50%g}. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the lentils, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water for the sauce{150%ml}. Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the liquid has reduced slightly, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Mix in the @creme fraiche{75%g} and @mango chutney{40%g}, then simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then remove from the heat.

Once the potatoes are cooked, add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the #potato pan{} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Drain in a #colander{}, then pop back into the pan. Add the @butter{20%g} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Gently mash together with a #potato masher{} - don't worry, it doesn't need to be smooth. This is your saag aloo topping!

Stir the roasted cauliflower into the lentil mixture and transfer to an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}. Spread the saag aloo evenly over the top.

Bake your pie in the oven until golden and bubbling, ~{5-6%minutes}. Once cooked, remove from the oven and allow to stand for ~{1%minute}.

Share between your plates and serve with the roasted carrots alongside. Enjoy!

> Our Indian Inspired Saag Aloo Pie is a delicious veggie option that makes it easy to eat more veg in your diet and try something new!